  

<h2 id="open-source-flexibility">Open source flexibility</h2>
<p>In part 2 of <em>Using todo.txt in Obsidian (Or Wherever You Like)</em>, I cover using the todo.txt format in apps both in <em>and</em> outside of Obsidian. <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/140-2025-01-20-todo.txt-in-obsidian-1">Click here for part 1</a>.</p>
<p>Seven years ago, my alter-ego (Oph√©lieD) left a long, glowing review on the Apple App Store for Michael Descy‚Äôs SwiftoDo Desktop app.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>SwiftoDo is wonderfully simple, and the sort and filter options are really useful. ‚Ä¶SwiftoDo for iOS is every bit as easy to use, and syncing through DropBox has so far been seamless between the two.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This was just a couple of years into my plain text journey, pre-Obsidian. The feature requests I mentioned in the review have since been addressed.</p>
<p>From 2017 to 2022 my plain text task management system gradually gained a bucketload of complexity. But oddly enough, more complexity led to less motivation! It wasn‚Äôt until simplifying right down that I was able to consistently focus on the work to be done, rather than the system for organising it.</p>
<p><span class="small-caps">FYI</span> SwiftoDo was last updated three years ago, not a good sign.</p>
<p>Even if the app has been abandoned, the beauty of the todo.txt format is that it‚Äôs open source, meaning that you‚Äôll never be trapped into one app and there are other options to choose from. <span class="small-caps">VS</span> Code, for example, has a nice todo.txt extension. Change the file extension from Obsidian‚Äôs&nbsp;.md to&nbsp;.txt, and the coloured syntax is ready to go.[^1]</p>
<p>SwifttoDo has a good feature set on Mac, however, and it also has a mobile app. See <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/140-2025-01-20-todo.txt-in-obsidian-1">last week‚Äôs post</a> for how to filter todo.txt tasks into usable subsets in Obsidian, using Bookmarks.</p>
<p>I had some syncing issues between SwiftoDo and Obsidian, so be careful if working with the same file in multiple apps! <!--I'm intentionally‚Äîand carefully‚Äîplaying with fire by keeping my Obsidian Synced vault in Dropbox, so that may well explain it.--> I noticed that a task deleted in the SwiftoDo iPhone app disappeared from the same file in Obsidian after a second or two, but a task added in Obsidian didn‚Äôt immediately appear in the SwiftoDo iPhone app. Sometimes the tasks I‚Äôd added in Obsidian on my Mac disappeared once the SwiftoDo iOS app finally got itself together! Nothing was lost as Obsidian created a conflicted file copy, but it‚Äôs not a great result.</p>
<p>Until I figure out what‚Äôs going on I‚Äôll avoid issues by waiting a couple of minutes or so after editing on my Mac before editing again via the SwiftoDo app on my phone, force closing the latter beforehand. Your mileage may vary, but this works for me. If any of this sounds too complicated or too risky, I suggest sticking with either SwiftoDo <em>or</em> Obsidian on both Mac and iPhone.</p>
<p><a href="https://apps.apple.com/app/sleek-todo-txt-manager/id1614704209?mt=12" target="_blank">Sleek</a> on the Mac appears to be just as capable as SwiftoDo, and sync has so far been okay. It‚Äôs a bit too eye-candy for my taste, but I‚Äôm sure I could get used to it.</p>
<p>As nice as pretty todo.txt apps like SwiftoDo and Sleek are, I also like using <span class="small-caps">VS</span> Code for working with tasks on my Mac. Being in that app multiple times a day with my plain text accounting records means that it‚Äôs both convenient and familiar. While I prefer the plainer options, it‚Äôs nice to have the choice. More than nice!</p>
<h3 id="todo.txt-might-not-be-for-you-but-then-again-it-just-might">Todo.txt might not be for you, but then again, it just might</h3>
<!--I'd heard about the todo.txt approach to managing tasks multiple times over the years before trying it out and I used it more than once, between playing with other tools.-->
<p>So should you give todo.txt a go?</p>
<p>Only if you are still calmly curious to see if it will work for you <em>after</em> reading <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/258880/11207328" target="_blank">this comment</a> from Steven Lowe (written in 2008, valid as ever today). I‚Äôve substituted his word<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>because‚Äù with<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>if‚Äù in the first sentence, to make it apply more generally.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Sorry to be the bearer of bad news, but a<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>simple and effective todo application‚Äù is so hard to find [if] you are using the tool as a substitute for self-discipline and commitment. Statements like<span class="push-single"></span> <span class="pull-single">‚Äò</span>I‚Äôve read parts of this and tried that and that and that but minor interface issues cause me to drop it in a few days‚Äô imply that you are looking for magic bullets and excuses.</p>
<ul>
<li>Minor issues with the tools are a poor excuse to abandon the effort.</li>
<li>Pick a system and a tool and&nbsp;<strong>stick with it</strong></li>
<li>No tool will give you the self-discipline and commitment necessary to change your habits</li>
<li>personal time-management is about changing your viewpoint and habits, not finding the<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>right‚Äù tool</li>
<li>caveat: some systems are more suitable than others for your personal work requirements. If you‚Äôre a developer, a calendar-based system like Franklin Planner is probably not going to work, while a list-based system like <span class="small-caps">GTD</span> probably will.</li>
</ul>
<p>Suggestion: google and review the various systems, pick one, and commit to it for at least a month. Try <span class="small-caps">GTD</span> and pen-and-paper, for example, then get fancy once the system is a habit. Once you know how you need to work the system and are committed to it, look for the perfect tool. In the meantime, the perfect tool is the enemy of the good practice, to mangle a quote&nbsp;;-)</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>[^1] Note that the Obsidian plugin that makes&nbsp;.txt files editable in Obsidian doesn‚Äôt allow you to use Bookmarks, so it‚Äôs useless in this case. You could keep your todo.txt (not&nbsp;.md) file in Obsidian, because a) it‚Äôs editable on mobile devices via the <em>open-as-md</em> plugin and b) sync and version control via however you‚Äôre syncing your Obsidian vault. Changing the extension back to&nbsp;.md only takes a second and immediately restores the bookmarks. I‚Äôm currently using a todo.txt.md file stored in my Obsidian vault, and editing it in SwiftoDo and <span class="small-caps">VS</span> Code on the Mac (or in whichever editor feels like fun on any given day).</p>
